Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a #small pot{} over medium heat. Stir in 1/4 tsp @cumin{1%tsp} (1/2 tsp for 4 servings); cook, stirring frequently, until fragrant, ~{30-60%seconds}.

> Be sure to measure the cumin—we sent more!

Stir in @white rice{1/2%cup}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, 3/4 cup water (1 1/2 cups for 4), a big pinch of @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to use in Step 3.

While rice cooks, in a #medium bowl{}, gently combine @ground beef{10%oz}, @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}, @Mexican spice blend{1%tbsp}, @water{1%tbsp} (2 TBSP for 4 servings), @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Form into two 1-inch-tall loaves (four loaves for 4).

Place meatloaves on a lightly oiled #baking sheet{}. Roast on top rack for ~{15%minutes} (you'll top the meatloaves with cheese then).

Once meatloaves have roasted 15 minutes, remove baking sheet from oven. Carefully top meatloaves with @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}; return to top rack and roast until cheese melts, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, fluff rice with a #fork{}. Stir in @butter{1/2%tbsp} (1 TBSP for 4 servings); taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if desired.

Divide rice, meatloaves, and @guacamole{4%tbsp} between plates. Top rice with @pico de gallo{4%oz}(draining first) and serve.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.